1AC w/ cites

Observation One: Death Worship

In spite of international legal rulings to the contrary, America currently retains a nuclear arsenal of 150-200 tactical weapons in Europe. These weapons are housed there under NATO nuclear sharing agreements. Current doctrine allows the number of recipient states for weapons to increase at NATO’s discretion.

Matousek 2000 http://www.inesap.org/bulletin15/bul15art12.htm

“besides the mentioned progress”...”for training purposes”

 

Matousek’s argument that NATO’s nuclear defense of a European claim to civilization is critical here because it’s NATO’s new raison d’etre – this creates a binary politics of a sacred self and a profane other.

Stanley Kober, 1998 http://www.cato.org/pubs/fpbriefs/fpb-046.html

“although Americans”…”sit at the back”

 

Crafting and policing a boundary between the West and the Rest replicates the discourse of sacred orders. America’s policy of extended deterrence is a manifestation of Russophobia, a closed-minded fear of Russia propagated by American elites to justify their continued hold on power. The contest with an imagined Russia has produced a narrative of life through death, where the only way to heal is to kill. This mindset cultivates the seeds of universal destruction.

Darrell Fasching, The Ethical Challenge of Auschwitz and Hiroshima, 1993, p. 115-120

“after Auschwitz and Hiroshima”…”planetary suicide”

 

Despite their oppressive nature, these weapons continue to be deployed under the delusionary belief that they uphold human dignity by perpetuating peace. The ethical paradigm which justifies nuclear deployments is based in a fearful, “realistic” assessment of global politics. IT conflates the world as it is with the world as it oughth to be, a practice which sanitizes killing in order to heal, and valorizes preservation of the status quo above all else. This system of rationalization has the power to pervert everything, from religion to all secular love of life into a justification for murder.

Fasching 93, above, p. 292-301

“it is no accident”…”for killing”

 

Observation Two is Hope:

Current American force postures demand that we speak out. Our weapons are forward deployed and menacing. Their presence in Europe turns that continent into a nuclear shield, designed to export violence away from the homeland. Removing weapons from Europe is the first step to taking responsibility for the nuclear state and for advancing an alternative.

Joel Kovel, Against the State of Nuclear Terror, 1984, p. 201-208

 “it is true that”…”of a nuclear assault”

 

Our plan is an embodiment of faith in a new way of living. It represents opening ourselves to strangers who we have thus far cast as enemies, and also opening ourselves to a future which will be radically different from our past. This openness allows us to transcend sacred, nationalist, militaristic narratives and replace them with holy ones that refuse the seduction of false gods like nuclear weapons in favor of peace.

Darrell Fasching, The Ethical Challenge of Auschwitz and Hiroshima, 1993 p. 287-290

“there is an ethical paradox”…”human interdependence”

 

By aligning our energies with an ethic of holiness, we plan the seeds of a new world. Holy communities have the capacity to rupture sacred orders and break our dependence on the state and its weapons.

Fasching, Narrative Theology after Auschwitz, 1992, p. 155-6

“this paradox is expressed”…”technical civilization”

 

Our affirmative is ultimately a call to reject the logic of the nuclear state; to be unreasonable in the face of terror, because reason has been perverted into madness, and must therefore be replaced. We cannot compromise, and we cannot give up.

Joel Kovel, above, p. 226-8

“this brings us to the subjective”…”land of its own”

 

Activating ourselves in struggle against nuclear terror is not about survival. It is about acknowledging something far deeper, which is the richness of life that turns survival into living. By agitating against the meaninglessness and insanity of the nuclear state, we break the bounds which tie us to it, and become truly free.

Joel Kovel, above, p. 155-6

“if this is the value”…”technocratic state”

Georgia CQ: TNWs                                 

 

Plan: Thus Robbie and I are “Resolved: That the USFG should enact removal of its tactical nuclear weapons from Europe.”

 

First sheet of paper, first division: debate, time, and the history of what would be.

 

Policy debate is not unlike Pavlov’s dog. Both react without serious critical thought to a certain behaviorist tradition. But while Pavlov’s dog salivates with the ringing of the bell, our timers sound our own obsession with prediction. We have inherited a legacy of politics that desires to map the future and treat political events within static spatio-temporal relations. Debaters speak of time-frame impact analysis, the risks of future consequences, and we pretend to “control” the direction of future links. Even the past is subservient to the future: empirical evidence tells us what will happen, and the present is only the anticipation of what will be.

 

But debate need not be this way. Our obsession with prediction has already undergone a crisis, evidenced by certain critical and performative arguments in debate. These approaches have done much to call the conventions of predictive politics into question. But two problems remain. First, these critiques fall back onto questions of prediction rather than representation and thus they problematize politics without forcing an investigation of time. This leaves intact leaves intact ways of thinking through time that ultimately reinforces the dominant logic of sovereignty.

 

R.B.J. Walker, Inside/Outside: International Relations as Political Theory, 1993, pp. 20-21

 

Second, these critiques presuppose an “outside” to the political. They argue for radical rethinking, and they identify some “other” space in which the political is displaced by the micropolitical. But these critiques win not by forcing a rethinking of the political but by reterritorializing it; they map politics into state-centered and other, into calculative and other. In so doing, these critiques become part of the same dialectic they allegedly oppose: they repeat the logic of division that keeps the state as a sovereign term, pretending that “we/they” are not always already constituted as subjects by our relationship to the state.

 

R.B.J. Walker, same cite, pp. 16-17

 

So on the one hand debate has the fantasy of the predictive future – what we might call Historicism, and on the other hand we have the fantasy of the critical rupture from the outside – what we might call Ahistoricism.

 

But we believe that advocacy need not be relegated to either of these loose categorizations. This affirmative is an attempt to rethink conventional politics by rethinking its relationship to time.

 

We contend that time should not be conceived as a straight line, linear in structure. History is not a chain of events, but rather, as Walter Benjamin tells us, “a single catastrophe which keeps piling wreckage and hurls it” at our feet (Theses on the Philosophy of History, IX). That wreckage is all too often assembled into narrative. But the unfortunate product is selective amnesia: some events fit better into the artwork that is historical narrative than others, and those others are often cast aside as unimportant and forgotten. Historicism pretends to know the future from its construction of the past, just as it pretends to be able to change the future based on this knowledge. But because the present, which is always changing, must coincide with both the interpretation of the past and the navigation of the future, the present must constantly be remade to affirm its own conditions. In this approach to political time, much like Hegel’s dialectic of history or the Manifest Destiny “progress” narrative, the present must ultimately be seen as better than the past, or at least better than alternative presents. This is what Susan Buck-Morss calls “vanguard time” – a conception of time that supports the logic of sovereign state power by constructing us as subjects constituted by our relationship to “official” history. This is the logic of most conventional policy debate – from the routine harms and solvency of 1AC’s to the banal scarecrows called disadvantages, and it is the same logic carried to a most pernicious extreme in the preemptive murders authorized by the Bush doctrine, which claims to know the future to which it responds.

 

Buck-Morss explains the political and ethical aspects of this logic in 2000:

 

Susan Buck-Morss, Dreamland and Catastrophe, pp. 66-67

 

Vanguard time’s monopoly over representation assumes that the future is preordained and objective. But the complex wreckage of history delights in resisting prediction and defying insertion into historical narrative.   Debate should follow suit, and we believe that, instead of locking in future meaning by playing the policy game or critiquing from the outside, ways of negotiating and reorienting our relationship to history need to be offered in order to reveal different insights into global politics.

 

Roland Bleicker, 2000, Popular Dissent, Human Agency, and Global Politics, p. 79

 

 

Second sheet of paper, second division: surprising the long march of history.

 

As Bleicker says, an international event can appear “in a new light once it is being scrutinized by an approach that pays attention to factors that have been hitherto ignored.” We believe that the presence of U.S. tactical nuclear weapons in Europe can be subject to such an investigation. The dominant narrative of continued progress as it relates to this policy reads as follows: the presence of those weapons maintains the transatlantic link with our allies and allows a European nuclear presence without requiring our European friends to cultivate their own nuclear stockpiles. Our TNW’s help deter Soviet nuclear and conventional aggression, keeping the Cold War cold and eventually forcing the Soviets to spend more on arms than their economy could handle. Eventually, thanks in part to the TNW’s assisted military supremacy of the West, the Soviet Union collapses, the Berlin Wall falls, and we arrive at the often celebrated “end of history.” Now the time for TNW’s has come and gone, their original purpose fulfilled, and a new evaluation of their present effectiveness is in order that paves the way for the reemergence of another political justification for their location in Europe and, subsequently, another grand narrative to complement this justification

But this story faces some problems. First, it transforms the present into evidence of the empirical success of the past, thereby ignoring all the little snapshots that don’t fit nicely into the movie version of the Cold War. Second, this narrative sells us more than just the past, present, and future of TNW’s; it also sells us a particular understanding of history structured by vanguard time and the all-encompassing power of narrative. We want to take Buck-Morss, Bleicker, and Walker seriously and problematize such a common accounting. We want to surprise this simple history of TNW’s with those snapshots it left behind. As such we will offer a few, often dramatic, often humorous, snapshots from the wreckage that Historicism has left behind:

 

Vignette One: Lakenheath

 

A retired US Air Force general described how an event at Lakenheath nearly caused widespread contamination of East Anglia. A B-47 bomber demolished a concrete weapons bunker, setting light to three Mark 6 nuclear bombs. The bombs survived the fire intact; the aircrew that fought the fire did not.

 

Another plan carrying a nuclear bomb caught fire while on the runway. The plane and the bomb burned long enough and intense enough for detonation but the bomb relinquished its right to explode.

 

One F-15 fighter jets dropped a training bomb in East Yorkshire, creating a crater 18 inches wide. This was not a pilot failre, but rather a mechanical failure; the dummy bomb simply fell off the plane while in flight. First Lieutenant Augustine Ekpoudom downplayed the incident, saying in a press statement that “public safety is our primary concern.”

 

 

Vignette Two: Counter-hegemonic actions and civilian inspections

 

The Center for Nuclear Disarmament conducted a series of actions around the NATO Defence Ministers Meeting held in Birmingham to draw attention to the contradictions and lack of progress on disarmament.

 

14 anti-nuclear organizations in a NATO-critical network have challenged NATO nuclear posture.

 

At NATO military headquarters in Belgium, 250 protesters were arrested for trying to conduct civilian inspections.

 

1, 117 protesters were arrested at Kleine Brogel military base in Belgium.

 

Peace activists were arrested outside Lakenheath after cutting through the perimeter fence to draw attention to the “illegal” nuclear weapons held there – all arrested there were later found guilty in a British court.

 

Vignette  _______: Targeting and Defense

 

Leo Szilar, the Hungarian physicist who realized how atom-splitting could help construct an atomic bomb, met with James Byrnes, Truman’s aide on atomic issues. The physicist was concerned with rumors that the military was targeting several Japanese cities for nuclear use and tried to persuade Byrnes that Japanese surrender could be achieved without massive loss of life. But the soon-to-be Secretary of State responded that the administration could hardly justify spending all its money in defense appropriations on technology that was not subsequently used for its original purpose.

 

 

 

These vignettes interrupt the conventional history of TNW’s, but they do not write a second history or tell a different future. We are not concerned with a linear genealogy of our nuclear policies, nor in reawakening the public to previous accidents and mistakes within nuclear history to reinforce their relationship with military policy or with the weapons. We are concerned with how these vignettes operate relative to the historical narratives governing TNW’s. Thus they are not advocacies in the traditional debate sense, but they relate the question of the resolution to our desire to participate in debate for the purpose of reorienting our perceptions of the past in order to understand differently the policies of the present. The ballot and the resolution can serve as a representation and a frame by which we might rethink these historical narratives and a practice by which debate might rethink its own temporal contours. Thus Robbie and I are “Resolved: That the USFG should enact removal of its tactical nuclear weapons from Europe.”

 

Our resolution opposes vanguard time with the “avant-guard,” the moments of displacement that interrupt, distract, or displace historical narrative. In the context of the vignettes, our avant-garde approach proposes a fragmented interpretation of history rather than History as narrative. Buck-Morss again in 2000. (pp. 67-69)

Thus we express our affirmation of the resolution as a repudiation of current US farm policy at its most foundational level.  In the most traditional sense of "affirmation," we advocate a significant change in the Status Quo:

 

A move away from the privileging of those voices that hold financial clout in the federal government.  A move toward the inclusion of perspectives too often ignored by US policymakers.

A move away from protecting the interests of those in power.  A move toward dismantling the socio and psychological barriers that entrench those sources of power.
